WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.800
I get a postcard to my home address and it says in all caps in dark black, we are watching you.

00:08.400 --> 00:09.380
Oh my God.

00:09.460 --> 00:09.680
I know.

00:09.820 --> 00:11.220
It was very unnerving.

00:11.420 --> 00:16.400
What do you think put you on the radar of any of these people?

00:22.060 --> 00:27.240
Dark Skies was an NBC series about an alien invasion set in the 1960s.

00:27.280 --> 00:28.300
Which you co-created.

00:28.300 --> 00:28.740
Yes.

00:28.740 --> 00:31.380
We're running the show and it's going to air that night.

00:31.480 --> 00:32.760
We say, let's have a party.

00:33.520 --> 00:38.520
I'm at a premiere party with all of these like big wigs in Hollywood and some guy walks out.

00:38.940 --> 00:41.440
And he says, you guys got a lot right.

00:41.920 --> 00:43.260
But you also got a lot wrong.

00:43.380 --> 00:44.300
And that's why I'm here.

00:44.440 --> 00:46.260
He just starts writing something on a piece of paper.

00:46.560 --> 00:50.240
And he goes, put this in a safety deposit box for about 10 to 15 years.

00:50.460 --> 00:51.220
I go, what is this?

00:51.240 --> 00:52.820
And he goes, secrets of the universe.

00:53.780 --> 00:54.180
Whoa.

00:54.640 --> 00:55.300
Good night, folks.

00:55.300 --> 00:58.900
They're going to tell us like when to write and how to write.

00:59.320 --> 01:00.400
So how would that work?

01:00.480 --> 01:05.180
You would give us ideas that you would want us to put in scripts.

01:06.080 --> 01:07.160
We didn't take the deal.

01:07.160 --> 01:13.240
Do you guys think that any other directors in Hollywood have taken similar deals?

01:13.240 --> 01:23.140
I am much more inclined now than I was when I made Close Encounters to really believe that we're not the only intelligent civilization in the universe.

01:23.140 --> 01:30.520
You know, after Jaws, apparently he got approached by some guys from Naval Intelligence or something.

01:30.780 --> 01:32.380
And he came and offered him a deal.

01:32.700 --> 01:33.840
And yeah, and he took it.

01:35.240 --> 01:39.060
We all just watched Steven Spielberg's Disclosure Day.

01:39.260 --> 01:43.100
And it's just like there are too many deep cut things.

01:43.280 --> 01:44.620
I think he got a lot right.

01:44.740 --> 01:46.240
No, he gets a lot right every time.

01:46.240 --> 01:50.380
I had a whole previous Disclosure experience when I was 18.

01:50.660 --> 01:54.700
We lived right next door to this family, a guy named John Harrington, his wife Lois.

01:54.700 --> 01:57.200
He goes, listen, I got a new job.

01:57.800 --> 01:59.700
I have a higher clearance level than the president.

02:00.600 --> 02:01.380
Aliens are real.

02:01.760 --> 02:02.280
They're here.

02:02.460 --> 02:03.200
And I've seen them.

02:03.640 --> 02:06.240
Reality is not what we know.

02:07.080 --> 02:10.880
This is what kicked off decades of high strangeness.

02:10.880 --> 02:17.300
I have seen six people die in pretty horrific ways, like Final Destination type.

02:17.540 --> 02:19.040
But I was in the middle of them.

02:19.220 --> 02:19.500
What?

02:19.960 --> 02:24.640
So I lower the paper and there's a woman standing at the foot of my bed.

02:25.920 --> 02:29.220
Her eyes are two black circles that are undulating.

02:30.920 --> 02:33.560
You also saw a Nordic alien?

02:34.460 --> 02:35.040
I did.

02:36.340 --> 02:37.620
On Orcas Island.

02:37.620 --> 02:38.620
And he said...

02:38.620 --> 02:47.900
How is this possible?

02:49.100 --> 02:50.800
Nothing too emotional about that.

02:52.960 --> 02:55.740
The existence cannot longer be denied.

03:04.700 --> 03:06.940
Bryce Zabel, thank you so much for being here.

03:06.940 --> 03:08.920
Brent Friedman, this is an honor.

03:10.040 --> 03:16.140
This couldn't be more perfect timing because we all just watched Steven Spielberg's Disclosure Day.

03:16.220 --> 03:19.960
And both of you guys have just illustrious Hollywood credentials.

03:20.620 --> 03:27.520
And we're here to talk about the connections between Hollywood and UFOs, but also a new amazing podcast that you guys have started about that.

03:29.000 --> 03:33.560
Bryce, you are the former chairman and CEO of the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences.

03:33.560 --> 03:39.500
You've created five primetime TV series, including Dark Skies, which you co-created.

03:39.760 --> 03:39.980
Yes.

03:40.180 --> 03:41.940
And it is just incredible.

03:42.080 --> 03:43.260
It's kind of a cult classic.

03:43.640 --> 03:45.320
And I want to get into a lot of themes there.

03:45.420 --> 03:48.200
You were a writer on Taken with Steven Spielberg.

03:48.200 --> 03:56.280
And you co-authored A.D. After Disclosure with Richard Dolan, obviously a legendary UFO researcher.

03:56.460 --> 03:59.280
I know you guys do a lot of media together as well.

03:59.820 --> 04:10.940
And Brent Friedman, you were a writer-producer, obviously Dark Skies, Mortal Kombat, Star Trek Enterprise, Star Wars, The Clone Wars, and many others.

04:10.940 --> 04:19.880
And you have some very interesting stories as well, which you guys share on your new podcast, Sound, Light, and Frequency.

04:20.260 --> 04:21.560
Thank you both for being here.

04:22.240 --> 04:22.880
Thanks for having us.

04:22.960 --> 04:25.060
This is a real pleasure for me.

04:25.240 --> 04:27.120
I'll let Bryce tell his own story.

04:27.260 --> 04:32.720
But I've been a fan of your show for a long time, listened to so many episodes, and learned a lot.

04:33.080 --> 04:34.740
We talk about your show all the time.

04:34.740 --> 04:40.980
And we keep doing shout-outs to your show on our show, because you are bringing it, and we're happy to be here.

04:41.220 --> 04:41.880
Thanks for having us.

04:42.020 --> 04:42.820
Where do we start?

04:42.940 --> 04:50.760
Maybe the title, Sound, Light, and Frequency, of the podcast, that came from a very interesting story.

04:51.420 --> 04:52.300
Let's get into that.

04:52.920 --> 04:54.880
You just made Dark Skies.

04:55.280 --> 04:58.600
You're doing this party, right, around its release, its premiere.

04:58.820 --> 04:59.040
Yep.

04:59.300 --> 05:00.380
And what happens?

05:00.460 --> 05:01.620
Somebody enters the scene.

05:01.620 --> 05:09.720
Well, I mean, the only thing you need to know is that Dark Skies was an NBC series about an alien invasion set in the 1960s.

05:11.200 --> 05:12.800
My name is John Lohengart.

05:13.240 --> 05:15.660
I'm recording this because we may not live through the night.

05:16.060 --> 05:20.480
They're here, they're hostile, and powerful people don't want you to know.

05:21.040 --> 05:23.080
History as we know it is a lie.

05:23.080 --> 05:39.240
So it was kind of, at the time, kind of a home run to have a network say, we're going to give you $40 million to make a bunch of subversive television because the pilot said JFK was killed because he was going to tell the truth about UFOs.

05:39.340 --> 05:40.740
So we're celebrating, right?

05:40.860 --> 05:41.740
We're on the air.

05:41.820 --> 05:42.720
It's a cool thing.

05:42.800 --> 05:47.420
There's buses driving around L.A. with our Dark Skies logo on it.

05:47.420 --> 05:48.300
And it's cool.

05:48.420 --> 05:49.120
It's a great thing.

05:49.180 --> 05:50.580
So we say, let's have a party.

05:50.740 --> 05:53.820
And we have it at my house, the same place I live today, all right?

05:53.900 --> 05:57.420
And there's 200 people in the backyard, which is a lot of people.

05:57.500 --> 05:58.220
It's a nice party.

05:58.340 --> 06:02.480
But Brent and I, we know every single one of them because we're running the show.

06:02.560 --> 06:06.140
And these are network executives, studio executives, what, casting crew?

06:06.140 --> 06:18.020
And we had a way to identify everybody because we did a party favor where when you'd come in, we took a little Polaroid photo of you and we turned it into a Majestic badge.

06:18.260 --> 06:21.400
In our show, it was about Majestic 12, right?

06:21.460 --> 06:23.040
The main characters were in Majestic 12.

06:23.160 --> 06:30.100
So everyone was walking around with a Majestic badge with their name and their photo on it, which is an important part of the story.

06:30.100 --> 06:34.460
Except for one guy, during the party, before the show has aired.

06:34.580 --> 06:40.520
So remember, nobody has seen this show, I mean, other than the production people, but it's not aired.

06:40.720 --> 06:42.360
And it's going to air that night.

06:42.420 --> 06:45.380
And we have TVs all over the place so that everybody can watch it.

06:45.760 --> 06:50.200
And one of our producers comes up to me and says, hey, there's a guy, you've got to meet this guy.

06:50.200 --> 07:03.260
And this guy introduces himself as JC, and he says, he just wanted to meet me to congratulate me on a successful show and says, you guys got a lot right.

07:03.960 --> 07:07.820
And he basically is saying that he has seen the pilot.

07:08.480 --> 07:08.940
All right.

07:09.240 --> 07:12.000
And I kind of challenged him.

07:12.060 --> 07:15.420
I said, well, if you've seen the pilot, what happens after that crop circle scene?

07:15.520 --> 07:17.360
And the guy goes, oh, yeah, that was great.

07:17.400 --> 07:19.060
They go back to the Majestic headquarters.

07:19.060 --> 07:21.040
They do that autopsy thing.

07:21.040 --> 07:23.020
And they pull the ganglion out of the guy's head.

07:23.140 --> 07:27.380
And I'm looking at him going, well, yeah, that's exactly what happens.

07:27.800 --> 07:29.540
And it was very unnerving.

07:29.920 --> 07:37.540
And the baton gets tossed to Brent here because I basically had 200 people in my backyard.

07:37.540 --> 07:39.580
I got people saying, where are the appetizers?

07:40.020 --> 07:44.520
And I've got people saying, you know, the network guy wants to talk to you and say something.

07:44.740 --> 07:45.620
So there's a lot going on.

07:45.680 --> 07:46.480
I don't know this guy.

07:46.500 --> 07:47.840
And I say, look, I don't know you.

07:47.840 --> 07:49.780
I don't know exactly why you're here.

07:49.900 --> 07:50.900
You were not invited.

07:51.040 --> 07:51.760
You should leave.

07:52.400 --> 07:56.080
And then I left and thought he'd escort himself out of the party.

07:56.200 --> 07:57.500
I had other things to do.

07:57.600 --> 07:58.820
But that's not what happened.

07:59.120 --> 07:59.940
Cut to Brent.

08:00.320 --> 08:02.360
This is my first TV series.

08:02.740 --> 08:05.080
So as Bryce said, huge TV.

08:05.260 --> 08:07.080
It's on NBC.

08:07.380 --> 08:09.460
It's the lead of their Thrilogy night.

08:09.460 --> 08:13.860
I'm at a premiere party with all of these, like, big wigs in Hollywood.

08:14.660 --> 08:19.560
But I've seen the pilot at this point a hundred times, right, through all the editing and the post-production.

08:19.820 --> 08:22.880
So I'm less interested in watching it on the monitors with everybody.

08:23.320 --> 08:24.860
But halfway through, I lose interest.

08:24.920 --> 08:30.680
And I'm thinking, I just want to find a place where I can, like, go out into the backyard and look at everyone and watch them watching it.

08:30.680 --> 08:36.740
So I go out by myself and I'm just standing out there and I hear a rustle in the bushes behind me.

08:36.840 --> 08:41.260
And I kind of turn around and some guy walks out and he does not have a majestic badge.

08:42.000 --> 08:45.420
And so I'm already thinking, I don't know who this guy is.

08:45.420 --> 08:47.480
Like, and he's like, hey, Brent, how's it going?

08:47.800 --> 08:50.480
And I'm like, and I don't know his name.

08:50.480 --> 08:54.480
And I'm thinking, is this like an NBC, like, marketing executive or something?

08:54.480 --> 08:55.400
But he knows me.

08:55.460 --> 08:56.440
I go, that's going pretty good.

08:56.460 --> 08:58.960
He goes, yeah, you guys got a lot right.

08:58.960 --> 09:13.720
Now, sidebar, in that moment, what that meant to me was, I had a whole previous disclosure experience when I was 18 with a guy who was a family friend that was in the Reagan administration.

09:13.720 --> 09:14.760
We can go into that later.

09:15.620 --> 09:17.620
But I took some of those ideas.

09:17.620 --> 09:21.980
I told Bryce over a lunch about them, which is what got us making Dark Skies.

09:22.080 --> 09:24.660
So there was some truth in the show.

09:25.560 --> 09:28.680
And this guy is suddenly standing there saying, you got a lot right.

09:28.680 --> 09:31.100
And then he says, you must have talked to someone.

09:31.740 --> 09:35.460
And I felt my whole stomach cinch up.

09:36.220 --> 09:37.720
Cue the eerie music.

09:37.860 --> 09:41.000
And I, right in that moment, I thought, I'm going to jail.

09:41.800 --> 09:45.660
Remember, I'm just like, I'm what, 40, 40, 35?

09:45.840 --> 09:46.860
I don't know, I'm like mid-30s.

09:47.100 --> 09:48.080
First TV show.

09:48.200 --> 09:51.060
And I'm thinking, here I am on the precipice of greatness.

09:51.060 --> 09:59.080
And there's some, he, because the guy looks like a cross between a frat guy and, you know, a typical FBI agent.

09:59.180 --> 10:01.660
Kind of clean cut, round 30.

10:01.860 --> 10:04.660
He's got a white press shirt, navy blue blazer.

10:05.200 --> 10:09.160
So what you're saying, other than me being above 30, like me, looks like me.

10:09.160 --> 10:10.100
You're too old to be as bad.

10:10.100 --> 10:11.720
He's got the jacket and the shirt and the cross.

10:11.720 --> 10:13.120
So here's this guy.

10:13.220 --> 10:16.220
And I'm like, I'm seeing my whole life flash before my eyes.

10:16.260 --> 10:18.680
And he goes, but you also got a lot wrong.

10:18.740 --> 10:19.780
And that's why I'm here.

10:20.280 --> 10:23.720
And I'm like, again, I'm thinking like, who is this guy?

10:23.920 --> 10:25.860
And so we start to talk.

10:25.920 --> 10:30.160
And he lays out that he is from the Office of Naval Intelligence.

10:30.160 --> 10:41.640
And they would like to talk to us about a deal where we could get access, we could get information that we could then help them with their slow drip disclosure program.

10:42.060 --> 10:50.740
And just to complete, now that the two stories kind of intertwine here, because the show is now on by the time Brent is talking to him at the barbecue.

10:50.740 --> 10:57.840
And I'm going back in the house to, I don't know what I'm doing, but I'm going back in and I look over and there's this guy I threw out of the party an hour ago.

10:57.840 --> 11:00.940
And he's talking to Brent and I'm thinking, that's not right.

11:01.040 --> 11:06.500
So now I joined this story and now you got Brent, me, and the guy who said he's from the Office of Naval Intelligence.

11:06.780 --> 11:09.560
And by the way, we are getting to sound light and frequency.

11:10.760 --> 11:12.240
So there I am.

11:12.320 --> 11:16.840
I'm talking to this guy and my wife comes up and she's looking for me.

11:16.900 --> 11:18.060
Bryce sees this guy.

11:18.380 --> 11:19.500
Suddenly my wife is there.

11:19.680 --> 11:26.080
So there's all these people talking and the guy says, yeah, so anyway, we'd like to make a deal with you.

11:26.220 --> 11:27.500
Here's my card.

11:28.280 --> 11:32.860
You know, and he gives me the card and all it says is J.C. with a 310 number on it.

11:32.920 --> 11:33.480
Nothing else.

11:34.240 --> 11:36.160
Give me a call and we can talk about it.

11:37.060 --> 11:41.860
And I kind of say, okay, you know, fine.

11:42.520 --> 11:47.520
And he kind of looks at me and his demeanor up until this point had been like, you know, fairly genial.

11:48.400 --> 11:53.100
Probably, by the way, because the guy that tried to throw him out of the party is now looking at him.

11:53.100 --> 11:59.760
So now he gets a little bit more serious and he says, I can see you're not taking this seriously.

12:00.260 --> 12:03.180
And he looks at my wife and he goes, ma'am, can I borrow a piece of paper and a pencil?

12:03.180 --> 12:12.820
She kind of like goes into her purse and she pulls out a piece of paper, which is she takes an old ATM deposit envelope, right?

12:12.820 --> 12:14.120
You have to put your checks in there.

12:14.120 --> 12:16.900
She rips off the triangular fold down.

12:17.300 --> 12:20.700
She gives him that and a pen and he takes it in front of all of us.

12:20.700 --> 12:24.080
And he just starts writing something on a piece of paper, about 30 seconds.

12:24.080 --> 12:26.440
And then he folds it up and he goes, here you go.

12:26.600 --> 12:27.200
Do me a favor.

12:28.040 --> 12:31.240
Put this in a safety deposit box for about 10 to 15 years.

12:31.320 --> 12:33.900
And if we don't make a deal, then you'll know I was for real.

12:34.520 --> 12:39.980
So I take it from him and I kind of look at it and I go, and it's an incomprehensible like formula thing.

12:40.360 --> 12:41.400
And I go, what is this?

12:41.420 --> 12:44.660
And he goes, sound, light, and frequency, secrets of the universe.

12:45.020 --> 12:45.640
Good night, folks.

12:46.080 --> 12:47.420
And he turns around and walks out.

12:47.760 --> 12:47.960
Wow.

12:48.180 --> 12:49.520
Is it a math formula?

12:50.360 --> 12:51.260
Not particularly.

12:51.260 --> 12:57.100
It's got some symbology in it and we're actually looking into it right now.

12:57.180 --> 13:01.140
I'd love to come back on your show someday and show it to you and explain what we're finding out.

13:01.140 --> 13:02.440
I want to see this thing.

13:02.640 --> 13:02.900
Yeah.

13:03.080 --> 13:05.280
You should use AI and try to decode it.

13:05.440 --> 13:08.060
We have done a lot of different things.

13:08.140 --> 13:09.100
We have a lot of people, right?

13:09.360 --> 13:11.460
Someone wrote a 22-page analysis of it.

13:11.480 --> 13:12.000
Oh, my God.

13:12.080 --> 13:12.300
I know.

13:12.660 --> 13:19.640
So it's weird and we can talk about that later, but I wanted to at least give you the understanding of what sound, light, and frequency meant.

13:20.060 --> 13:20.420
Right?

13:20.420 --> 13:27.600
Why we named the podcast this, because this is what kicked off decades of high strangeness, starting with that show.

13:27.680 --> 13:31.900
Now, I'm an experiencer, so my high strangeness started going all the way back to when I was a child.

13:32.100 --> 13:41.140
But it all kind of culminated in dark skies and brought Bryce into this crazy experience that lasted, that went on for a while.

13:41.140 --> 13:43.960
Because that was not the only time we talked to JC.

13:44.360 --> 13:45.400
To what happened next.

13:46.100 --> 13:49.600
Actually, it's almost important to talk about what happened before.

13:49.700 --> 13:53.700
A year before that event, we were shooting the dark skies pilot.

13:54.040 --> 13:54.260
Okay?

13:54.540 --> 13:59.460
And by the way, we're not here to talk about a 30-year-old show other than it exists in a framework.

13:59.520 --> 14:01.800
Well, everybody should watch it because it's a really great show.

14:01.800 --> 14:03.120
It is fun, but it exists in a...

14:03.120 --> 14:10.300
And it's predictive, I think, of a lot of things that seem to really dovetail with real whistleblower accounts.

14:10.360 --> 14:10.660
Absolutely.

14:10.660 --> 14:23.420
And as we've been sort of, I guess we're using the Soundlight and Frequency podcast as a bit of an investigative, active investigation to try to see if we tell our story, will other people tell us their stories?

14:23.520 --> 14:25.260
And that's actually starting to work.

14:25.520 --> 14:29.320
Anyway, things we had forgotten almost were this one.

14:29.400 --> 14:35.420
A year before, when we're shooting the pilot, I get a postcard to my home address.

14:35.420 --> 14:42.580
And it's got a picture on the front cover, which, by the way, you should put that on your show if you want.

14:42.700 --> 14:42.920
Yeah, yeah.

14:42.940 --> 14:47.940
And it's a picture of a book, I believe from 1960, called Flying Eyes.

14:48.160 --> 14:51.780
And it's these eyes flying in the sky looking at whatever.

14:52.060 --> 15:01.400
And I turn it over to read the postcard, and it's been typed on an old-style manual typewriter with a very black ribbon, and it's all in caps.

15:01.400 --> 15:09.200
And it's not like Tom Hanks used in Band of Brothers and all that, that kind of old thing.

15:09.320 --> 15:17.680
And instead of it being a sentence that goes across all in caps, it's four words, one, two, three, four, stacked on top of each other.

15:17.760 --> 15:22.440
And it says in all caps in dark black, we are watching you.

15:22.440 --> 15:36.280
So Brent, of course, was thinking about his interaction with this guy that was the Secretary of Energy during the Reagan administration and wondering about that.

15:36.480 --> 15:38.940
I'm thinking about these postcards that we got.

15:39.100 --> 15:41.380
So this guy didn't come out of nowhere, right?

15:41.580 --> 15:41.820
Yeah.

15:41.880 --> 15:42.900
Did not come out of nowhere.

15:42.900 --> 15:48.700
What do you think put you on the radar of any of these people?

15:48.820 --> 15:49.640
Do you think it would work?

15:49.820 --> 15:52.520
Had you already written, taken with Spielberg?

15:52.520 --> 15:54.940
Well, no, that came after.

15:55.060 --> 15:55.360
That came after.

15:55.620 --> 15:58.300
But I had done a couple of UFO things.

15:58.400 --> 16:04.940
And, of course, Brent and I were at that moment doing a very highly anticipated pilot.

16:05.220 --> 16:08.160
People were talking about it because of the way we sold it was interesting.

16:08.300 --> 16:09.220
But that's another story.

16:09.220 --> 16:13.900
But prior to that, I had written the first Sci-Fi Channel original film.

16:14.000 --> 16:15.200
And it was called Official Denial.

16:15.400 --> 16:17.420
And it was highly ufological.

16:17.680 --> 16:26.620
I mean, it had everything from Majestic 12 to abductions to crash wreckage and organic spaceships and all the stuff in it.

16:26.680 --> 16:28.220
So put that on the radar.

16:29.140 --> 16:33.820
I'd even written UFOs and Men in Black into the Lois and Clark series when I worked there.

16:33.820 --> 16:38.560
So I was sort of a UFO guy in making, you know.

16:38.740 --> 16:40.600
And then we got Dark Skies.

16:40.740 --> 16:42.700
So maybe that's what put us on the radar.

16:42.740 --> 16:44.540
On the radar of the powers that be.

16:44.560 --> 16:44.920
Of somebody.

16:44.980 --> 16:45.140
Right.

16:45.440 --> 16:46.020
Of somebody.

16:46.120 --> 16:46.520
That's right.

16:46.600 --> 16:48.320
Bryce was doing a lot of work in this area.

16:48.500 --> 16:50.640
I had literally done no work in this area.

16:50.780 --> 16:55.820
But, again, I should bring you up to speed on this when I got disclosed to.

16:55.820 --> 17:00.340
Because, obviously, it was relevant to somebody.

17:01.160 --> 17:07.140
And it has come full circle now because Dave Grush has been asking me about this person.

17:07.600 --> 17:08.860
So he should tell you the story.

17:08.960 --> 17:10.380
And I just want to give you one quick setup.

17:10.980 --> 17:12.460
Brett and I did not know each other.

17:12.540 --> 17:17.000
His wife was my assistant on a show called Mantis that I was producing.

17:17.180 --> 17:19.600
And she knew I had all these UFO books in the office.

17:19.600 --> 17:21.260
And she said, you should meet my husband.

17:21.260 --> 17:26.820
So we went out to lunch and he told me the story that he's going to tell you right now.

17:26.920 --> 17:30.180
And when I heard it, I went, I don't even know who this guy is.

17:30.360 --> 17:32.080
I don't even know if this story is true.

17:32.320 --> 17:34.540
It's a hell of a story and I'd like to work with him.

17:34.580 --> 17:37.600
And that became our origin, if you will.

17:37.640 --> 17:38.560
Yes, that was our meet cute.

17:38.600 --> 17:39.120
That was our meet.

17:40.200 --> 17:41.200
Hollywood parlance.

17:41.200 --> 17:41.920
But he did meet.

17:43.020 --> 17:45.000
So here's the story.

17:45.000 --> 17:45.260
Yeah.

17:45.780 --> 17:51.160
I grew up next to a guy that I revered when I grew up in the Bay Area.

17:51.740 --> 17:54.420
In a place called Walnut Creek, which is East Bay.

17:55.220 --> 18:05.260
And we lived right next door to this family where there was a guy named John Harrington, his wife Lois, his two daughters.

18:05.480 --> 18:06.200
I'm not going to name them.

18:07.500 --> 18:11.120
His daughters were in between my brother and I.

18:11.220 --> 18:12.940
So I was the oldest of the four kids.

18:13.060 --> 18:13.980
My brother was the youngest.

18:14.500 --> 18:18.400
And I mean, we literally lived right next door and there was like one gate between us.

18:18.640 --> 18:20.980
And we lived on these pretty big pieces of property.

18:20.980 --> 18:22.640
So we didn't have any other real neighbors.

18:22.760 --> 18:24.380
It was just us, kids growing up.

18:24.940 --> 18:27.420
And John was a man's man.

18:27.620 --> 18:30.320
He was all the things I wanted to be.

18:30.360 --> 18:31.220
My dad was an artist.

18:31.620 --> 18:33.040
And so I wanted to be an athlete.

18:33.140 --> 18:33.820
I wanted to do all these things.

18:33.960 --> 18:39.680
John taught me how to throw a football, got me into football, taught me how to hold a gun, you know, shoot a BB gun.

18:39.780 --> 18:40.680
Just all these things.

18:40.840 --> 18:43.620
And loved my dad, but he was an artist.

18:43.760 --> 18:45.280
He wasn't interested in any of this stuff.

18:45.280 --> 18:48.860
So I became, he was the, he was like a surrogate father to me.

18:49.860 --> 18:52.820
Cut to, we move away six years later.

18:53.020 --> 18:54.320
We stay in touch, the families.

18:55.160 --> 18:57.120
And then I get a phone call.

18:57.300 --> 18:58.580
I've just graduated from high school.

18:58.680 --> 18:59.320
It's 1981.

19:00.020 --> 19:01.160
And I'm going to UCLA.

19:01.580 --> 19:07.620
And I had, John had suggested that I go to Stanford, which was his alma mater, but I'm going to UCLA to be a theater major.

19:07.620 --> 19:11.540
So he calls me up and he says, you know, what are you doing?

19:11.600 --> 19:13.120
And I can't believe you didn't go to Stanford.

19:13.320 --> 19:15.720
He goes, listen, I got a new job.

19:15.900 --> 19:17.160
I'm back East now.

19:18.220 --> 19:23.800
And I'd, I'd like you and maybe a couple of friends to drive our cars across the country.

19:24.000 --> 19:30.120
Oh, and our dog, bringing our dog with you and some other stuff that we left in the garage, but I'll pay you guys.

19:30.120 --> 19:34.360
And then when you get back here, I'll show you around DC and then I'll fly you back.

19:34.620 --> 19:36.500
I'm thinking, what a great summer.

19:36.500 --> 19:37.980
Sweet deal for a college kid.

19:37.980 --> 19:38.180
Right.

19:38.280 --> 19:41.160
It's like, uh, it was the in between high school and college.

19:41.160 --> 19:42.800
So I'm thinking, sure, I'll, I can do that.

19:43.280 --> 19:58.980
So he didn't say anything about what his job was, but actually we knew something was going on because about a year earlier or so we had been approached the family by some like NSA or like CIA or someone that come in and asked a bunch of questions.

19:58.980 --> 20:05.140
I guess they were doing like a background character check on him, but they didn't tell us what the job was, but we knew it was something with the government.

20:05.140 --> 20:08.100
And he has just moved back to Langley Farms, Virginia.

20:10.100 --> 20:20.360
So by the way, in, in 1981, we now know John Harrington was the undersecretary of the Navy for, I believe, development and, or procurement or something like that.

20:20.360 --> 20:24.260
And I, I believe he went through Stanford on a Naval ROTC scholarship.

20:24.640 --> 20:25.040
Okay.

20:25.180 --> 20:25.960
So Navy.

20:26.840 --> 20:30.660
And he will later become the secretary of energy in the second term.

20:31.340 --> 20:32.140
Department of Energy.

20:32.340 --> 20:32.760
There you go.

20:32.760 --> 20:35.680
So none of this means anything to me.

20:35.740 --> 20:36.700
He's just a great friend.

20:36.800 --> 20:38.020
He's like my surrogate dad.

20:38.560 --> 20:39.700
The drive across the country.

20:39.860 --> 20:42.980
I don't know why we weren't killed or put in jail many times.

20:43.640 --> 20:45.460
That's a whole other movie I've never written.

20:46.140 --> 20:47.440
We get to his house.

20:48.200 --> 20:53.300
That night when he comes home where everyone's waiting to have dinner, because it's going to be like this reunion.

20:53.300 --> 21:04.680
And, um, I remember kind of like waiting at the window, kind of waiting to see when I was in a black Lincoln town car pulls up and he gets out of the backseat and there's two secret service people that come in.

21:04.760 --> 21:07.420
And I noticed he has a briefcase handcuffed to his wrist.

21:08.100 --> 21:15.020
They walk him into the house and into kind of the, off the entryway into his office and they go back and I'm kind of watching from a distance.

21:15.100 --> 21:16.420
No one will even make eye contact with me.

21:16.440 --> 21:20.700
And I'm watching from a distance and he puts it into a wall safe, right?

21:20.700 --> 21:24.280
One of the secret service people leaves and the other one stays in the house.

21:25.660 --> 21:27.840
I'm thinking, who is this guy?

21:28.120 --> 21:30.680
Like, but he comes, hey, Brian, how's it going?

21:30.840 --> 21:32.960
We have a big dinner and everything's great.

21:33.040 --> 21:37.520
And then afterwards he's like, hey, why don't you and I go out onto the veranda and catch up?

21:38.440 --> 21:44.820
So when we were growing up, he was not just like pad-ass, but he was Calvinist.

21:44.860 --> 21:48.020
So he was very strict about certain things.

21:48.020 --> 21:54.100
We go into the back patio and he brings a big bottle of Jim Beam and he's pouring himself two fingers as we're talking.

21:54.520 --> 21:56.060
He looks haggard.

21:56.180 --> 22:00.520
He looks, you know, old, like very much older, but also just heavy now.

22:01.420 --> 22:02.480
He's a different guy.

22:04.320 --> 22:06.080
I'm sitting there talking with him.

22:06.160 --> 22:06.780
We're catching up.

22:06.820 --> 22:09.020
He's giving me shit about not going to Stanford.

22:09.480 --> 22:11.700
And I'm like, okay, all of that's great.

22:12.140 --> 22:13.400
What is your job?

22:13.740 --> 22:15.560
And he goes, I can't really talk about it.

22:15.560 --> 22:20.260
I, you know, it's, I'm working for the government now he was Reagan's advance man in his campaign.

22:20.380 --> 22:22.820
He was one of the reasons that he helped Reagan get elected.

22:23.140 --> 22:31.080
There's a whole history between John's wife, Lois Haight, who's, I think one of her family members was a governor of California back in the day.

22:31.080 --> 22:35.060
And so politics, Republican, you know, they went way back.

22:35.060 --> 22:38.860
At any rate, he's working for Reagan because Reagan trusts him.

22:39.640 --> 22:41.760
And this is a super smart guy.

22:42.260 --> 22:46.400
And now he's telling me, I can't tell you what the job is.

22:47.260 --> 22:48.120
It's classified.

22:48.580 --> 22:51.400
And I said, okay, well, I don't, what does that even mean?

22:51.420 --> 22:54.740
And he goes, look, I have a higher clearance level than the president.

22:54.740 --> 22:59.320
Now, 1981, oops, 18 years old.

22:59.420 --> 23:01.280
I was not a standout in civics.

23:01.420 --> 23:03.380
I was like, that's impossible.

23:03.480 --> 23:06.100
The president, there is nothing higher than the president.

23:06.840 --> 23:12.640
How, how, how could the guy who lived next door to me have higher classification than the president?

23:12.640 --> 23:15.280
But this is not a guy who lies.

23:15.760 --> 23:18.880
Like, so I'm looking at this guy and I'm thinking, what?

23:19.320 --> 23:20.840
I'm like, okay.

23:21.700 --> 23:24.900
And I said, well, how did, so how did you get that job?

23:24.980 --> 23:31.040
And he said, well, I, I was briefed for months in an underground facility in West Virginia.

23:33.020 --> 23:35.400
Again, this is the guy you grew up with.

23:35.400 --> 23:39.400
Like this, I'm like looking at this person, like, I don't, I don't even know who this man is anymore.

23:39.400 --> 23:43.840
And I said, what, what was that like?

23:43.880 --> 23:46.300
And he said, well, I used to cry myself to sleep every night.

23:47.440 --> 23:58.080
That's, by the way, when he said that to me at this lunch, I just got shiver, you know, because a tough guy is crying himself to sleep every night.

23:58.560 --> 24:00.540
What's it take for that to happen?

24:00.900 --> 24:01.080
Yeah.

24:01.120 --> 24:01.280
Yeah.

24:01.380 --> 24:06.720
And even if he's exaggerating, I couldn't have imagined him crying himself to sleep once.

24:06.900 --> 24:07.080
Right.

24:07.080 --> 24:11.420
So I said, well, I don't, what, what would make you cry yourself to sleep?

24:11.460 --> 24:16.020
And he goes, Brent, this is not the, the world I thought I was bringing my daughters into.

24:18.060 --> 24:20.900
I'm thinking, well, I'm like your son.

24:22.500 --> 24:25.020
What is this world that we're in?

24:25.460 --> 24:28.040
And so I pressed him on and he kept saying, I can't talk about that.

24:28.080 --> 24:28.900
I can't talk about it.

24:28.940 --> 24:30.700
I can, this is like classified information.

24:30.700 --> 24:41.480
And finally, after he'd had a couple of drinks, he said, all right, look, I know when you were growing up, you were into science fiction and comic books and all that stuff.

24:41.740 --> 24:42.620
I can tell you this.

24:43.220 --> 24:44.020
Aliens are real.

24:44.220 --> 24:44.920
They're here.

24:45.040 --> 24:45.880
And I've seen them.

24:45.880 --> 24:48.060
Just like that.

24:48.680 --> 24:50.360
Just like here, I'll throw you a bone kid.

24:51.480 --> 24:56.620
Now I honestly, at that point in my life, I hadn't thought a lot about aliens.

24:56.740 --> 24:57.920
I wasn't into aliens.

24:58.060 --> 25:02.680
This wasn't a thing in my life, but this felt huge.

25:02.680 --> 25:04.280
Like I couldn't wrap my brain around it.

25:04.280 --> 25:07.580
And I said, well, are they alive?

25:08.160 --> 25:12.140
And he paused and he said, I can't say.

25:12.940 --> 25:14.860
I said, you can't say or you won't say.

25:14.900 --> 25:16.160
And he said, I can't say.

25:18.000 --> 25:20.500
And I kind of just left at that.

25:20.640 --> 25:24.120
And then I came back at him with, okay, well, hold on a second.

25:24.880 --> 25:29.440
If what you're saying is true, how does everyone not know about it?

25:29.560 --> 25:31.500
And he said, oh, lots of people know about it.

25:31.500 --> 25:37.160
81, you could walk into any bookstore and you're going to find all sorts of books on

25:37.160 --> 25:38.440
the shelves with lots of truth.

25:38.820 --> 25:43.140
But right next to them are the books that we publish full of propaganda.

25:43.520 --> 25:46.600
It's a multi-billion dollar campaign to cover up the truth.

25:47.840 --> 25:53.420
Now in 81, I, the other thing that struck me was I didn't, I don't know that I'd heard

25:53.420 --> 25:54.820
the term billion before.

25:55.220 --> 25:58.980
So I'm like, like everything is blowing my mind right now.

25:58.980 --> 26:05.340
And I'm thinking what, like I just had not considered any of this.

26:05.340 --> 26:10.120
And I was like, okay, why is the truth have to be covered up?

26:10.740 --> 26:12.940
Like you're telling me, okay, aliens are real.

26:13.000 --> 26:13.960
Okay, great.

26:14.120 --> 26:14.560
What else?

26:14.900 --> 26:19.440
And he said, look, we live in a God fearing country.

26:19.440 --> 26:27.820
Again, 1981, there's only one thing that keeps this world spinning, gives everybody the control

26:27.820 --> 26:28.360
they need.

26:28.600 --> 26:30.020
That's the global economy.

26:30.400 --> 26:37.260
If you disrupt that by taking away the reason for people to live their lives, everything

26:37.260 --> 26:41.280
falls apart and governments of the world will not be able to control the populace.

26:41.280 --> 26:47.040
So what's the advantage of giving people the truth?

26:47.600 --> 26:50.920
And I was like, well, so you're telling me it'll never come out?

26:51.400 --> 26:52.760
He said, if it has to.

26:53.500 --> 26:55.520
I said, well, in our lifetime, maybe.

26:56.640 --> 27:00.200
And why would he tell you, an 18 year old, if he's classified?

27:01.100 --> 27:02.320
What did you ask him?

27:02.460 --> 27:04.160
I asked, so I, well, yes.

27:04.160 --> 27:09.380
So one other, he's telling me all of this and I just, each thing is just like a brick

27:09.380 --> 27:10.060
on my shoulder.

27:10.200 --> 27:13.440
I'm just like, this is a lot to process.

27:14.960 --> 27:16.580
And I said, wow.

27:16.760 --> 27:17.140
Okay.

27:17.260 --> 27:20.980
Well, I guess now I know why you cried yourself to sleep every night.

27:21.120 --> 27:23.840
And he said, no, Brent, you don't understand.

27:23.960 --> 27:25.000
This was day three.

27:28.660 --> 27:33.440
He'd been there for months and I'm thinking, okay, I'm out.

27:34.760 --> 27:35.880
I'm like, I can't.

27:36.160 --> 27:40.120
And I said, well, I, you know, how do you know I'm not going to tell anybody this?

27:40.180 --> 27:41.380
And he goes, I'm sure you will.

27:41.860 --> 27:43.240
Question is, who's going to believe you?

27:43.300 --> 27:44.420
You're an 18 year old kid.

27:44.520 --> 27:45.540
You're going off to college.

27:45.920 --> 27:47.140
You're going to tell a big story.

27:47.560 --> 27:48.600
You use my name.

27:48.720 --> 27:49.520
I'll just deny it.

27:51.060 --> 27:55.920
Now, in the years following that, I did tell a couple of people and they were like, wow,

27:55.920 --> 27:56.780
that's such a great story.

27:56.780 --> 27:58.380
And I could tell no one believed me.

27:59.020 --> 28:02.200
And I just started to just lose interest in even telling the story.

28:02.200 --> 28:04.520
Because like, all you end up looking like is an idiot.

28:05.540 --> 28:10.720
Although I did make Brent tell it to me multiple times because I wanted to see if it ever changed.

28:11.180 --> 28:15.480
If this, if this, you know, I'm a journalist by training.

28:15.480 --> 28:22.920
So I thought if he tells it multiple times and it's, it's something he's riffing on, then, then the riff will change a little bit, but it never has.

28:23.260 --> 28:29.920
And, uh, uh, recently a couple of things have even happened that make us more sure than ever that it's a true story.

28:29.920 --> 28:31.180
Yeah. Share some of that.

28:31.540 --> 28:37.540
Well, I mean, the one thing that's most obvious, and Jesse, you must know this yourself, uh, your, all your, many of your audience does.

28:37.700 --> 28:44.360
There are underground facilities in West Virginia, but we did not know about them until the Washington Post.

28:44.660 --> 28:49.480
I think it was the Post that broke this story in the nineties about Greenbrier Inn.

28:49.600 --> 28:55.480
And there's an, another one at Greenbrier was where they were going to evacuate Congress in the event of nuclear war.

28:55.480 --> 28:58.960
So there was a place, but in 1981, nobody knew that.

28:59.220 --> 29:00.540
Do you think he was talking about Greenbrier?

29:00.820 --> 29:05.680
He didn't say, but again, he was talking about an underground facility in West Virginia.

29:06.740 --> 29:11.420
I didn't, you, I couldn't have shown you on a map where West Virginia was at that time.

29:11.540 --> 29:14.560
I did not know there were such things as underground facilities.

29:14.780 --> 29:18.980
So when I told it to Bryce, I, that was probably just part of the story.

29:19.060 --> 29:25.240
But then it was years later when it actually came out, like Bryce said, that the, there's a whole story and now you can go visit it.

29:25.240 --> 29:26.700
It's like a tourist place.

29:26.820 --> 29:27.760
We could do a show from there.

29:28.000 --> 29:35.580
Do you think what freaked him out so much dealt with the fact that he had this Calvinist Christian background?

29:36.660 --> 29:44.640
Or do you think there's something much darker than just aliens at the surface level of what he sort of was briefed on?

29:44.920 --> 29:46.360
So excellent question.

29:46.520 --> 29:48.340
It's the, it's the question we get a lot.

29:48.340 --> 29:49.260
I get a lot.

29:49.260 --> 29:55.800
Um, and I, you know, I regret having not followed up with him to ask that question.

29:56.080 --> 29:58.060
I frankly was just too overwhelmed.

29:58.060 --> 30:01.280
I was like, you know, it's the whole drinking from a fire hose thing.

30:01.340 --> 30:03.160
I just had too much information too fast.

30:03.860 --> 30:05.120
What was your instinct though?

30:05.180 --> 30:12.980
Cause I, I often, you know, like before you rested the aliens thing out of him, he's saying, this is not the world.

30:12.980 --> 30:18.420
I thought I was bringing my daughters up in, are you, you, your mind must be racing.

30:18.560 --> 30:19.800
Like, what is he talking about?

30:19.880 --> 30:22.980
Are you thinking anything specific there?

30:23.360 --> 30:37.060
No, I think at that, at that moment, I, I didn't have, I, my imagination wasn't developed enough to even, you know, start to think, well, is it, are we in a matrix or, you know, I didn't have any of that language.

30:37.060 --> 30:37.460
Right.

30:37.540 --> 30:40.020
To, I just was like, well, what does that mean?

30:40.080 --> 30:41.840
What I, all I knew is I don't like it.

30:42.100 --> 30:44.520
I don't, I don't like what, what he's talking about.

30:44.600 --> 30:54.260
And so I didn't have an opinion then since then I have developed many ideas and theories, but, and people have asked me too, like, well, how do you know he wasn't lying to you?

30:54.280 --> 30:55.640
How do you know this wasn't a psyop?

30:56.100 --> 31:06.840
Well, technically I don't, but again, it's the, I think why I set the story up with the context is that I had a really strong relationship with this guy.

31:07.300 --> 31:07.700
Right.

31:08.680 --> 31:11.360
For him to use me as part of a psyop.

31:11.420 --> 31:15.620
And by the way, what's my value as a psyop as an 18 year old student?

31:15.740 --> 31:17.760
I'm not, it's not even like I'm going into film school.

31:17.860 --> 31:18.940
I'm going to theater.

31:20.140 --> 31:24.560
Like, so I'm absolutely worthless on, on every level, but particularly him.

31:25.000 --> 31:28.980
So I have to scratch that off and say, well, he wasn't, I wasn't a psyop.

31:29.100 --> 31:31.100
And then I go, why would he lie to me?

31:31.380 --> 31:31.740
Right.

31:31.760 --> 31:33.560
Like that's such a weird, specific lie.

31:33.680 --> 31:34.200
No reason.

31:34.200 --> 31:38.420
So then I'm into, why did he even disclose to me?

31:38.480 --> 31:41.380
Well, it sounded like he needed to unburden himself.

31:41.600 --> 31:46.140
He left haggard and run down and he wasn't this man's man that you had grown up with.

31:46.340 --> 31:51.980
So you can imply, as I do, that by saying this isn't the world I thought I was bringing my daughters into.

31:52.120 --> 31:53.360
Well, how do you protect your daughters?

31:53.460 --> 31:55.160
You don't share any of this information.

31:55.380 --> 31:59.900
So my guess is that he probably hadn't shared anything with his wife or his daughters.

31:59.900 --> 32:02.040
Well, I'm, they were only my age at that point.

32:02.240 --> 32:04.900
And so who does he talk to, right?

32:04.940 --> 32:05.700
Who is that outlet?

32:05.800 --> 32:11.460
I mean, at the end of the day, this is a super smart guy, badass, very successful, but he's human.

32:12.020 --> 32:12.380
Right.

32:12.440 --> 32:14.780
And he's having to carry, and he's a lot of integrity.

32:14.980 --> 32:19.380
He's having to carry these stories, which are, as he's saying, lies, right?

32:19.400 --> 32:20.680
The public is being lied to.

32:20.720 --> 32:22.240
I'm sure that doesn't make him feel good.

32:22.240 --> 32:35.480
Um, but I think in, in the intervening years, my theory has gone to the truth that he had to process was that reality is not what we know, right?

32:35.540 --> 32:37.200
That includes history.

32:37.200 --> 32:40.880
That includes the things we're being taught in school, just everything.

32:40.880 --> 32:45.120
And I, I think that is what would make him cry.

32:45.120 --> 32:50.720
Like how, this is not the, this is, I brought kids into a world I thought I understood.

32:51.560 --> 32:55.220
The rules of that world are not at all what I thought.

32:55.320 --> 33:02.040
And now my ability to protect those children, to bring them up and give them the life I had is gone.

33:03.380 --> 33:04.840
So, wow.

33:04.840 --> 33:16.040
There is a piece of information, though, that just has come out in the last couple of years and is active today that actually, uh, lends great credibility to this story.

33:16.420 --> 33:18.800
Um, can I go into that for a second here?

33:18.800 --> 33:18.860
Sure.

33:18.960 --> 33:19.080
Yeah.

33:19.080 --> 33:19.300
Okay.

33:19.540 --> 33:29.420
So in, uh, in 2023, I was doing, uh, the need to know, uh, show with Russ Coulthard and, uh, Coulthard had a source who you have now met.

33:29.420 --> 33:37.300
It was David Grush and David Grush was coming out to Los Angeles to, uh, be interviewed by Ross on News Nation.

33:37.640 --> 33:48.940
And the day before he had come out and everybody had lunch and then they decided, well, you know, we should put him on tape now for either practice or as an emergency piece of tape in case he gets arrested.

33:49.080 --> 33:53.500
He too was worried about being arrested before he went to record with Ross.

33:53.500 --> 33:57.980
So everyone went to my house, the same place where this party crasher crashed, right?

33:58.160 --> 34:04.080
And, uh, and my son was the, the guy that recorded Dave Grush on his first interview.

34:04.580 --> 34:10.300
During the time when we were getting ready to record that, I said, have you ever heard of John Harrington?

34:10.760 --> 34:13.680
And Grush said, oh, I know, I know John Harrington.

34:13.680 --> 34:15.680
I said, well, what, what, what do you know about him?

34:15.900 --> 34:16.840
He didn't want to talk about it.

34:16.900 --> 34:17.060
Okay.

34:17.080 --> 34:19.220
Now let's flash forward to 2025.

34:19.220 --> 34:39.880
Um, I'm not even, I don't think I'm even working with Coulthard anymore when this happened, or maybe, maybe I was, but he calls me and he says, I've been asked by Dave Grush to ask you to ask Brent if he can help us get John Harrington to Washington DC to potentially testify to the house oversight committee.

34:40.080 --> 34:45.520
Well, I don't think you'd do that if, if it's just a wacky story made up by a kid.

34:45.740 --> 34:46.900
No, you definitely wouldn't.

34:46.900 --> 34:51.320
Also assistant secretary of the Navy, you'd probably be at the heart of the matter.

34:51.500 --> 35:09.360
And then, and then you go on to be the secretary of energy, like, you know, the Navy comes up, uh, it was Bob Lazar, the Navy comes up, uh, you know, Nat Kobitz, who is a, uh, you know, a senior Navy scientist who was kind of Ross Coldhart's original source that really brought him down the rabbit hole.

35:09.360 --> 35:14.320
Uh, you know, he was Navy, uh, Harold Malmgren said, you know, office of Naval intelligence.

35:14.320 --> 35:16.020
That's where all the secrets are kept.

35:16.120 --> 35:20.640
Office of Naval intelligence is the oldest, uh, intelligence agency in the United States.

35:20.640 --> 35:23.600
It goes back to, I think like 1881 or two or something.

35:23.600 --> 35:26.480
So yeah, all, all of that makes sense.

35:26.540 --> 35:33.660
And then of course you have all of the rumors that the Manhattan project was the kind of original UFO legacy program.

35:33.880 --> 35:46.220
And the Atomic Energy Commission outlined this sort of restricted data where if you were to collect anything that had any radiological features, alpha, beta, gamma radiation, it would be born secret.

35:46.220 --> 35:54.340
But there's just so much meat on that bone when it comes to both Navy and, you know, Atomic Energy Commission, which turns into the DOE.

35:54.520 --> 35:56.100
So it just makes sense.

35:56.300 --> 36:01.140
And by the way, when that, when the guy who said he was from ONI said, you got some things right.

36:01.140 --> 36:06.760
One of the things he said we got right is we had the, the guy running Majestic 12 be from the Navy.

36:07.240 --> 36:07.720
Okay.

36:08.120 --> 36:08.980
And they thought that was-

36:08.980 --> 36:09.480
Inspired by John Harrington.

36:09.900 --> 36:11.080
Inspired by John Harrington.

36:11.080 --> 36:11.380
There you go.

36:11.620 --> 36:13.660
And you got to add the final piece here.

36:13.880 --> 36:15.640
John Harrington, not John Harrington.

36:15.640 --> 36:17.660
And Dave Grush called you this year.

36:17.820 --> 36:18.180
Yeah.

36:18.320 --> 36:18.920
You should-

36:18.920 --> 36:20.040
In the last couple of weeks.

36:20.340 --> 36:20.660
Really?

36:20.680 --> 36:24.160
You should fess that up because I don't think anyone's, you've not said that to anybody.

36:24.580 --> 36:25.740
It was a little unsettling.

36:25.820 --> 36:28.580
I get an email saying, I've got a matter I want to talk with you about.

36:28.680 --> 36:29.400
I'm like-

36:29.400 --> 36:30.080
From Dave Grush.

36:30.140 --> 36:30.980
Yeah, from Dave Grush.

36:30.980 --> 36:35.140
And I was like, I hope I don't have to go talk in front of a bunch of people.

36:35.300 --> 36:37.300
I'm, I'm, did not want that.

36:37.760 --> 36:44.320
And so I call him up on the Signal app and he explains to me, I can't say everything he said,

36:44.320 --> 36:50.680
but he, he said to me, the gist of it was, we've identified John Harrington as one, as

36:50.680 --> 36:57.580
a very important person who has oral history of a period where a bunch of documentation

36:57.580 --> 36:59.000
does not exist anymore.

36:59.000 --> 37:02.760
And we would like to talk to him, right?

37:02.840 --> 37:03.940
And I will go to him.

37:04.000 --> 37:04.840
He doesn't have to come.

37:05.300 --> 37:08.500
I'm asking you because you know him well, you had a relationship.

37:08.980 --> 37:11.880
How would I go about even getting him to talk?

37:11.960 --> 37:17.400
Because five or six years ago, Marco Rubio tried to approach him and that he got shut

37:17.400 --> 37:17.700
down.

37:18.300 --> 37:21.120
So I really want to talk to him.

37:21.240 --> 37:23.820
Now, John is in his mid eighties at this point.

37:23.820 --> 37:27.260
Um, his wife maintained a relationship with my mom.

37:28.020 --> 37:34.140
Um, and I got through secondhand information that John wasn't in great health.

37:34.600 --> 37:41.180
So I'm sure there's a little urgency to like get his story on the record, but I also understand

37:41.180 --> 37:42.480
he doesn't want to tell his story.

37:42.640 --> 37:46.380
If he wanted to tell his story, he would have been like Harold Malmgren, Malmgren was with

37:46.380 --> 37:48.260
you, like coming forward and volunteering.

37:48.260 --> 37:49.880
He hasn't done that.

37:50.540 --> 37:56.380
And it goes back for me to maybe he hasn't told his family about any of the things that

37:56.380 --> 37:58.460
he did and he does not want to.

37:58.540 --> 37:59.960
And that's his right and privilege.

38:01.100 --> 38:01.280
Wow.

38:01.420 --> 38:02.500
This is so fascinating.

38:02.640 --> 38:07.900
It's almost like he was maybe majestic 12 or at that, that, that level, you know, you

38:07.900 --> 38:09.900
have Bobby Ray Inman who was Navy.

38:09.900 --> 38:17.140
And then he ended up as, uh, I believe, uh, he was both, uh, director of the CIA and director

38:17.140 --> 38:21.860
of the NSA at the same time, I think, or maybe he was deputy director of the CIA and, and

38:21.860 --> 38:22.580
director of the NSA.

38:23.340 --> 38:27.520
And, uh, you have, you have all of these guys who seem like they're high up in the Navy and

38:27.520 --> 38:31.100
then they are, you know, are all over this issue in this sort of lore.

38:31.420 --> 38:35.860
And so I wonder how, how much, you know, and it's interesting too, that he wanted you to

38:35.860 --> 38:36.500
go to Stanford.

38:36.640 --> 38:37.620
Do you ever think about that?

38:37.620 --> 38:41.380
Like maybe he was like grooming you a little bit and he was like, why didn't you go to

38:41.380 --> 38:41.740
Stanford?

38:42.360 --> 38:44.760
Maybe you could have gone down the same road I did.

38:45.300 --> 38:46.420
That's a great theory.

38:46.800 --> 38:48.800
I have, no one has ever proposed that.

38:48.880 --> 38:49.740
That's really interesting.

38:49.740 --> 38:50.280
I like that.

38:50.620 --> 38:53.540
Have you thought, have you thought about it independent of me bringing it up?

38:53.580 --> 38:56.620
No, I'm saying no one has asked it and I had not thought of it.

38:56.620 --> 38:56.920
Uh-huh.

38:57.380 --> 38:58.200
I'm thinking of it.

38:58.200 --> 38:59.660
There was at one point, so he was a lawyer.

38:59.680 --> 39:00.700
Because you were like a son to him.

39:00.820 --> 39:01.100
Yes.

39:01.280 --> 39:06.400
Well, he, there was, he was a lawyer and he wanted me to follow in his footsteps and go to,

39:06.400 --> 39:09.560
he went to like Bolt or Hastings law school at Cal.

39:09.760 --> 39:15.660
So he went to Stanford, um, you know, apparently with three point, a 4.0 in three years, like

39:15.660 --> 39:19.700
that kind of guy, top of his class, Bolt or Hastings, I think it was Bolt.

39:19.960 --> 39:23.520
And he kept, had always been telling me, you should be a lawyer, you know, take over my

39:23.520 --> 39:28.720
practice or work in my, so maybe, maybe I was heading down that path.

39:28.780 --> 39:29.260
I don't know.

39:29.260 --> 39:34.300
So, you know, people have said over the years, like, why you, why would he talk to you?

39:34.420 --> 39:35.960
I think it's your theory is correct.

39:36.080 --> 39:43.020
I think in that moment, here's this kid he has a relationship with, he can just unburden

39:43.020 --> 39:43.240
himself.

39:43.240 --> 39:45.220
We're sitting out on the back porch, right?

39:45.700 --> 39:47.580
And he just unburdens himself.

39:48.000 --> 39:53.500
And at the same time, I think in this, he didn't want to tell his family about this, but

39:53.500 --> 39:55.660
here's this young man going off to college.

39:55.660 --> 39:58.120
It's like, here's some things you should know, kid.

39:59.120 --> 39:59.320
Right.

39:59.400 --> 40:07.220
And, and to get even trippier, a lot of these things seem woven together on this hermetically

40:07.220 --> 40:10.140
sealed level of like serendipitous interactions.

40:10.380 --> 40:10.620
Yes.

40:10.660 --> 40:14.600
And it, sometimes it deals with kind of like old money, old families, that sort of thing.

40:14.780 --> 40:19.940
And if he is married to Lois Haight, is this of like the Haight-Ashbury, the same name?

40:19.940 --> 40:20.660
So it's spelled the same way.

40:20.660 --> 40:26.100
And there's sort of this, you know, almost royal Californian, you know, like king-making

40:26.100 --> 40:27.120
family like that.

40:27.180 --> 40:28.680
That seems kind of interesting as well.

40:29.600 --> 40:31.040
And it's very interesting.

40:31.320 --> 40:36.420
I don't, this is, as we've talked about, not just the story, but a lot of the things that

40:36.420 --> 40:42.340
have happened to us, there's a point where you get the tipping point of coincidence.

40:42.680 --> 40:42.900
Yeah.

40:42.900 --> 40:47.000
And you go, okay, this cannot logically be a coincidence.

40:47.220 --> 40:50.960
All of these things, these connections and whatnot, you're into this thing where it's

40:50.960 --> 40:54.160
like, it's either synchronicity or it's designed.

40:54.680 --> 40:55.020
Yeah.

40:55.080 --> 40:58.240
And it's designed at a level that's higher than you.

40:58.340 --> 40:58.620
Yes.

40:58.740 --> 41:03.800
We were just talking earlier, you know, about, you know, you being the chair of the Academy

41:03.800 --> 41:05.100
of Television Arts and Sciences.

41:05.100 --> 41:11.420
And, you know, the last writer to do it was Rod Serling, who I knew was my dad's godfather,

41:11.520 --> 41:17.540
but I didn't know that he had produced this sort of, you know, preeminent UFO documentary

41:17.540 --> 41:21.460
in 1974, UFOs, Past, Present, Future, until I had gotten into the subject.

41:21.700 --> 41:26.060
So there are all these things, you know, I've experienced similar things and you can't even

41:26.060 --> 41:26.740
talk about it.

41:26.800 --> 41:31.080
And then it also feels a little self-indulgent and people start to think that you're like

41:31.080 --> 41:35.140
part of the conspiracy and it's not, it's happening at a higher, a higher level.

41:35.460 --> 41:41.000
And by the way, there's just one little Harrington note that you should point out during Dark

41:41.000 --> 41:42.280
Skies, you heard from him.

41:42.720 --> 41:43.080
Yes.

41:43.320 --> 41:43.580
Okay.

41:43.700 --> 41:45.800
So this, this was interesting.

41:46.460 --> 41:48.580
We're in the middle of production on Dark Skies.

41:48.680 --> 41:50.080
I think it's just started to air.

41:50.520 --> 41:51.980
There's a lot of press at the time.

41:52.280 --> 41:56.520
And I come in and there's on my desk at the production office, there's an envelope from

41:56.520 --> 41:57.080
John Harrington.

41:57.480 --> 42:00.600
I'm like, this is another like, like.

42:01.080 --> 42:03.500
Oh, I, you betrayed everything that I told you.

42:03.580 --> 42:04.960
And instead I open it up.

42:05.020 --> 42:06.500
It's one of those old buck slips, right?

42:06.520 --> 42:07.740
From the desk of John Harrington.

42:07.740 --> 42:12.540
And it's like this long strip and it says, congratulations, Brent, on finally getting your

42:12.540 --> 42:14.340
story, your story out there.

42:14.820 --> 42:16.940
Whoa, no way.

42:17.220 --> 42:17.380
Yeah.

42:17.540 --> 42:18.400
So he, okay.

42:18.640 --> 42:23.560
Well then this, clearly this JC, you know, office of Naval intelligence guy was probably

42:23.560 --> 42:24.000
acting.

42:24.000 --> 42:29.040
He was probably aware of, and John Harrington were aware and in coordination around the fact

42:29.040 --> 42:31.700
that you had been, you know, informally briefed.

42:31.700 --> 42:31.760
Yeah.

42:31.880 --> 42:34.020
This is the question that we can't answer.

42:34.260 --> 42:36.800
And I'd love an answer if someone could provide it.

42:38.060 --> 42:39.900
Did JC know John Harrington?

42:40.060 --> 42:41.460
Was there any coordination there?

42:41.460 --> 42:45.380
I think there had to, because if you think about it, if he's saying I'm office of Naval

42:45.380 --> 42:50.640
intelligence and then John has this like, you know, kind of illustrious, you know, amazing

42:50.640 --> 42:52.400
history at the highest levels.

42:52.620 --> 42:52.680
Yeah.

42:53.660 --> 42:58.460
And then he's, you know, saying like, it's almost like you were fed some of this information

42:58.460 --> 43:02.220
and then you were fed a little bit of the information, at least enough to get interested

43:02.220 --> 43:03.340
when you were a teenager.

43:03.580 --> 43:03.620
Yeah.

43:03.620 --> 43:08.300
Uh, and then, and then John simultaneous to that is writing to you and he hadn't gotten

43:08.300 --> 43:09.400
in touch for a while.

43:09.720 --> 43:13.960
And so he's saying congrats on getting your story out as if he's knowledgeable about the

43:13.960 --> 43:15.880
whole story, dark skies and all of it.

43:16.020 --> 43:19.160
That all seems, you know, not coincidental to me.

43:19.280 --> 43:22.720
Is that buck slip came just after the JC contact.

43:22.880 --> 43:27.380
So part of what's so interesting, like, again, we wouldn't be telling a story because, hey,

43:27.500 --> 43:30.040
we, it's nostalgic that this'll be fun.

43:30.040 --> 43:36.180
It's because these events like barnacles on a ship have just attached itself to the story.

43:36.280 --> 43:42.700
So there's the story of a UFO alien invasion TV series that it told, but that's only part

43:42.700 --> 43:48.380
of the story because Brent and I were part of the synchronicity, this lightning rod for

43:48.380 --> 43:49.560
some of these other things.

43:50.060 --> 43:55.320
Um, and, and as we've gone forward with our own, you know, uh, investigation of this, we

43:55.320 --> 44:00.620
have found other people who have other similar kinds of stories.

44:01.260 --> 44:03.860
I want to close the loop on the JC story.

44:03.940 --> 44:04.180
Yes.

44:04.280 --> 44:07.040
Cause I'm sure a lot of the audience is like, whatever happened with that?

44:07.140 --> 44:07.280
Yeah.

44:07.340 --> 44:11.740
Did you take the, the Faustian bargain and end up working with him or what happened

44:11.740 --> 44:11.980
next?

44:11.980 --> 44:13.360
There's two beats to that story.

44:13.360 --> 44:18.340
As we say in Hollywood in the week following JC coming to the party.

44:18.340 --> 44:21.140
So now we go back to work, right?

44:21.240 --> 44:25.220
We, you know, it's hard to make even bad television, but if you aspire to make good

44:25.220 --> 44:30.500
television, it's, it's all encompassing because think about it at any given time, you're shooting

44:30.500 --> 44:34.360
one episode, you're in post-production on another episode, you're on pre-production

44:34.360 --> 44:35.220
on something else.

44:35.340 --> 44:37.620
You've got a writer's room knocking out scripts.

44:37.780 --> 44:39.360
There's just a lot of work, right?

44:39.400 --> 44:40.880
So we sort of moved on.

44:41.180 --> 44:45.800
We just said, I don't know what that was, but let's forget about it and move on.

44:45.800 --> 44:51.180
And, and, uh, uh, I believe it was your assistant that got a phone call from JC.

44:51.400 --> 44:51.720
Yes.

44:51.840 --> 44:53.320
Who, who suggested a meeting.

44:53.600 --> 44:53.860
Yes.

44:53.940 --> 44:59.260
Well, so JC, first of all, we were very rattled when I, once we were able to kind of talk and

44:59.260 --> 45:01.440
debrief after that first meeting, we were a little bit rattled.

45:01.560 --> 45:03.640
So he called, I did not call him.

45:03.820 --> 45:04.540
He gave me the card.

45:04.620 --> 45:05.380
I did not call him.

45:05.440 --> 45:06.460
He called a couple of times.

45:06.680 --> 45:09.260
So my assistant finally came in and said, it's that JC again.

45:09.260 --> 45:14.660
And I'm like, so I go in and I take the call and he's like, Hey, listen, um, uh, we

45:14.660 --> 45:19.000
would like to follow up on our meeting and I'm going to bring a superior over to your

45:19.000 --> 45:21.360
office and we can have another discussion.

45:21.400 --> 45:23.200
I was like, okay, but we're click.

45:23.240 --> 45:24.320
Like it wasn't.

45:25.360 --> 45:26.360
Let's set a meeting.

45:26.360 --> 45:29.080
It was, I'm coming over to do this thing.

45:29.080 --> 45:29.420
Right.

45:29.440 --> 45:32.840
And he gave me a day and a time and it wasn't negotiable.

45:33.340 --> 45:37.260
And part of the problem, part of the setup was that he, I think he was saying, I think

45:37.260 --> 45:39.380
your partner needs a little bit of convincing.

45:39.380 --> 45:39.820
Right.

45:40.000 --> 45:43.080
Cause I, I'd been sort of the blocking character in this story.

45:43.160 --> 45:43.360
Right.

45:43.540 --> 45:48.520
And so they did come to our offices that I believe it was the week after this party.

45:48.820 --> 45:53.900
And, uh, what, what Brent and I decided to do is, uh, okay, we had a conference room

45:53.900 --> 45:57.040
and had, you know, the glass window and everything, which we thought was good.

45:57.140 --> 46:00.280
That'd be a good place to meet with these people if, if they showed up.

46:00.280 --> 46:04.480
Cause we posted our security guys, uh, from the, the show.

46:04.540 --> 46:07.060
We said, just stand outside and look tough.

46:07.060 --> 46:07.460
Right.

46:07.500 --> 46:09.900
So they were, so there were witnesses too.

46:10.000 --> 46:13.340
We thought if anything untoward is going to happen, we don't want to, you know, we want

46:13.340 --> 46:13.880
to see this.

46:14.000 --> 46:15.700
And so this guy did show up.

46:15.800 --> 46:18.820
JC showed up the young, youngish 30 ish guy.

46:18.920 --> 46:25.680
And he showed up with a guy who we would, I say 10 to 15 years, maybe, you know, uh,

46:25.680 --> 46:26.100
older.

46:26.380 --> 46:31.640
And this guy, uh, you know, JC gave off sort of the intelligence vibe.

46:31.780 --> 46:34.920
The guy that he brought out gave off more of a military vibe.

46:35.120 --> 46:35.960
We'll call him the captain.

46:35.960 --> 46:39.720
We call him, we didn't call him in the meeting, the captain, and maybe he was introduced as

46:39.720 --> 46:39.940
that.

46:40.020 --> 46:43.440
We've called him that since because we, we don't want to call him the guy in the bomber

46:43.440 --> 46:43.900
jacket.

46:43.900 --> 46:44.300
Right.

46:44.460 --> 46:47.920
But he had a bomber jacket with insignias and all that boots, jeans.

46:47.920 --> 46:55.500
And he was, um, if JC was willing to have a friendly conversation and was the good cop in

46:55.500 --> 47:00.440
this, this guy was the bad cop because he sort of acted like, I can't believe I have

47:00.440 --> 47:02.600
to be here and talk to you guys.

47:02.860 --> 47:08.720
And so, but they were still there to sort of make a deal or to talk about it.

47:08.860 --> 47:12.940
And so remember we told you earlier where, uh, they had said, you got a lot of things

47:12.940 --> 47:13.200
right.

47:13.200 --> 47:16.200
So we were like, well, you know, what, what did we get right?

47:16.800 --> 47:20.000
And, uh, so there was some conversation about that.

47:20.040 --> 47:22.360
But at one point the guy, he said, well, I'll tell you what you got wrong.

47:22.800 --> 47:23.200
Right.

47:23.200 --> 47:30.200
And we had had this thing, which was a horror kind of trope, which was the, the alien organism

47:30.200 --> 47:34.320
embedded in your brain and could be copied and sent to other humans.

47:34.320 --> 47:37.680
It was classic invasion of the body snatchers kind of thing.

47:37.760 --> 47:38.440
And he said.

47:38.660 --> 47:39.160
The ganglion.

47:39.260 --> 47:39.960
The ganglion.

47:40.240 --> 47:40.340
Yeah.

47:40.400 --> 47:43.740
And this is the thing he said that I got both of us kind of taken aback.

47:43.800 --> 47:45.760
He goes, that's not the way it's done.

47:45.880 --> 47:46.260
Hmm.

47:46.800 --> 47:48.360
And we're like, okay.

47:48.520 --> 47:49.660
Did you say, how is it done?

47:49.680 --> 47:49.800
Yeah.

47:49.800 --> 47:50.240
How is it?

47:50.240 --> 47:50.720
We did.

47:50.840 --> 47:57.140
And he, he, he, they said implants and it was, it was more technological, uh, some kind

47:57.140 --> 47:57.720
of implants.

47:58.180 --> 48:03.940
And the only thing I can tell you is again, both Brent and I were in a different state

48:03.940 --> 48:04.440
of mind.

48:04.760 --> 48:07.600
Uh, we didn't have proof that this was real.

48:07.740 --> 48:08.140
Right.

48:08.160 --> 48:12.720
