01:05:27.400 --> 01:05:32.440
It's just a big ranch kind of rolling fields out, you know, near the grapevine.

01:05:33.040 --> 01:05:36.280
And we're looking for a place where we can shoot our crop circle sequence.

01:05:36.360 --> 01:05:37.780
We have a big crop circle sequence.

01:05:38.440 --> 01:05:41.860
And so we find this big field and everything's great.

01:05:42.120 --> 01:05:47.540
At the end of that location scouting day, we go down to like a roadhouse down in Newhall.

01:05:47.840 --> 01:05:49.960
And we're having dinner or lunch or whatever it was.

01:05:50.200 --> 01:05:52.860
And I'm sitting with Toby because he's a friend of mine.

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:57.500
I developed a script with him that was going to be a low budget independent horror film.

01:05:57.500 --> 01:05:58.820
And we become good friends.

01:05:58.820 --> 01:06:00.220
And he was a great guy.

01:06:00.220 --> 01:06:05.460
So we're sitting there and all the producers, Bryce, everyone else is kind of talking.

01:06:05.640 --> 01:06:11.340
And I said to him, so Toby, you're finally going to have one up on Steven.

01:06:11.420 --> 01:06:15.360
Because I know he's very competitive with his buddy Steven Spielberg.

01:06:16.200 --> 01:06:17.480
And he goes, what do you mean?

01:06:17.520 --> 01:06:21.200
And I said, well, you're going to be the first one to put a crop circle on film.

01:06:22.360 --> 01:06:24.080
And he hasn't done that yet.

01:06:24.080 --> 01:06:27.000
And he's like, yeah, I'm never going to beat Steven in that category.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:29.160
And I go, what do you mean?

01:06:29.220 --> 01:06:29.400
Why?

01:06:29.440 --> 01:06:34.520
And he goes, uh, you know, after Jaws, he, you know, he was like really big deal.

01:06:34.520 --> 01:06:38.140
And he, apparently he got approached by some guys from Naval Intelligence or something.

01:06:38.140 --> 01:06:40.040
And they came and offered him a deal.

01:06:40.600 --> 01:06:40.900
And, uh.

01:06:40.900 --> 01:06:42.300
Did he actually say Naval Intelligence?

01:06:42.380 --> 01:06:42.780
Yes, he did.

01:06:42.780 --> 01:06:43.080
Oh, he did.

01:06:43.160 --> 01:06:43.400
All right.

01:06:43.460 --> 01:06:43.580
Wow.

01:06:43.780 --> 01:06:45.540
And, uh, and yeah.

01:06:45.560 --> 01:06:48.960
And, and he took it and he, he, you know, he got, he got all sorts of information.

01:06:48.960 --> 01:06:51.320
I mean, close encounters is based on a true story.

01:06:51.580 --> 01:06:52.400
And I was like.

01:06:53.920 --> 01:06:54.240
What?

01:06:54.440 --> 01:06:55.060
And he goes, yeah.

01:06:55.140 --> 01:06:56.500
I mean, ET too.

01:06:56.500 --> 01:07:00.180
Like he got access to a bunch of really like interesting case files and stuff.

01:07:00.600 --> 01:07:01.480
And, uh, yeah.

01:07:01.940 --> 01:07:05.680
So this is all happening before we are approached.

01:07:06.200 --> 01:07:06.600
Right.

01:07:06.640 --> 01:07:11.060
And so then this is all part of what's going through my head when the guy says, I'm here

01:07:11.060 --> 01:07:12.440
with Office of Naval Intelligence.

01:07:12.440 --> 01:07:17.380
And so now kind of swing it all the way around and ask that question again.

01:07:18.460 --> 01:07:19.780
Would you take the deal?

01:07:19.920 --> 01:07:21.380
Well, I don't know.

01:07:21.680 --> 01:07:24.380
Our show got canceled at the end of one season.

01:07:24.380 --> 01:07:24.680
Right.

01:07:24.680 --> 01:07:25.720
We didn't take the deal.

01:07:26.100 --> 01:07:28.860
I'm not saying that that's a guarantee for success.

01:07:29.240 --> 01:07:34.400
And I'm not saying that Steven Spielberg's success, massive success, isn't purely based

01:07:34.400 --> 01:07:35.100
on talent.

01:07:35.560 --> 01:07:42.240
But in terms of the deal and having access to information, we already know other people

01:07:42.240 --> 01:07:42.780
have come forward.

01:07:42.860 --> 01:07:44.200
We weren't the only ones offered the deal.

01:07:44.200 --> 01:07:45.240
And why would we be?

01:07:45.240 --> 01:07:47.380
Well, it gets even crazier, right?

01:07:47.500 --> 01:07:54.660
Because Dark Skies, there was active intervention on behalf of Steven Spielberg where you had

01:07:54.660 --> 01:08:00.080
to redo a whole season to adequately differentiate it from his projects.

01:08:00.240 --> 01:08:02.160
This is a painful story, to be honest.

01:08:02.300 --> 01:08:05.540
Brent and I have not told this story ever until this year.

01:08:05.540 --> 01:08:14.280
We sort of took the vow when we went down this road to, not because our ideas are the only

01:08:14.280 --> 01:08:17.800
ideas out there, but we just said, if we're going to tell this story, if we're going to

01:08:17.800 --> 01:08:21.780
demand transparency from other people, then we better be fully transparent.

01:08:22.140 --> 01:08:26.400
And if you're going to really look at the Dark Skies thing from those postcards to the

01:08:26.400 --> 01:08:32.960
Harrington aspect and to the JC approach and the Admiral and the Cemetery at Midnight,

01:08:32.960 --> 01:08:37.180
there's a piece of that puzzle and it happens in the summer.

01:08:37.640 --> 01:08:41.740
Well, the first time it happened actually was back during that pilot shooting.

01:08:42.080 --> 01:08:47.640
And I got a phone call on the set and it was the Columbia TV executive.

01:08:48.320 --> 01:08:50.720
And he said, listen, we have a problem.

01:08:52.300 --> 01:08:53.580
They're making a movie.

01:08:53.740 --> 01:08:56.340
It's a comedy called Men in Black at Sony.

01:08:56.520 --> 01:08:57.620
Now that's where we were.

01:08:57.900 --> 01:08:59.040
Columbia was under Sony.

01:08:59.180 --> 01:09:01.180
So at the same production entity.

01:09:01.180 --> 01:09:07.140
And, um, they're, they're very upset and you need to get your guys out of the black

01:09:07.140 --> 01:09:07.940
suits today.

01:09:08.060 --> 01:09:12.780
Now we had called our guys in the script, Men in Black, and we were shooting them in

01:09:12.780 --> 01:09:18.980
black suits and skinny ties and sometimes in sunglasses, sometimes in hats, but we were

01:09:18.980 --> 01:09:20.940
mostly, they were men in black.

01:09:20.940 --> 01:09:26.340
And I went into as, as, you know, chapter and verse, well, men in black doesn't belong to

01:09:26.340 --> 01:09:26.860
anybody.

01:09:26.860 --> 01:09:33.560
It goes back to the fifties, Maury Island and Gray Barker and all the stuff that you're

01:09:33.560 --> 01:09:34.060
aware of.

01:09:34.060 --> 01:09:36.100
And the many people in your audience are aware of.

01:09:36.380 --> 01:09:42.360
And the guy cuts me off and he goes, Bryce, let me put this in words that you can understand,

01:09:42.480 --> 01:09:45.220
which is about the most condescending thing you could say to anybody.

01:09:45.220 --> 01:09:48.960
But I've been insulted by experts in Hollywood, so it didn't really faze me.

01:09:49.040 --> 01:09:50.760
But what he said next really did.

01:09:51.120 --> 01:09:52.140
And this is a quote.

01:09:52.300 --> 01:09:54.720
This is, it's seared in my head.

01:09:54.960 --> 01:10:01.920
He says, get your guys, get, no, get your actors out of the black suits today, or we

01:10:01.920 --> 01:10:05.100
will shut down your production and burn your negative.

01:10:07.060 --> 01:10:07.540
Jesus.

01:10:08.060 --> 01:10:08.320
Yeah.

01:10:08.800 --> 01:10:10.360
That's not, we're going to cancel your show.

01:10:10.460 --> 01:10:12.180
We're going to remove all evidence.

01:10:12.180 --> 01:10:12.940
And delete you.

01:10:12.940 --> 01:10:13.980
Yeah, exactly.

01:10:14.220 --> 01:10:15.120
We're going to delete you.

01:10:15.620 --> 01:10:16.600
From reality.

01:10:17.360 --> 01:10:18.380
That's crazy.

01:10:18.760 --> 01:10:19.920
We're going to men in black you.

01:10:20.080 --> 01:10:22.480
If you don't get your men in black, get out of the show.

01:10:22.640 --> 01:10:23.160
Right on.

01:10:23.220 --> 01:10:23.940
It was terrifying.

01:10:24.080 --> 01:10:29.180
I mean, it was really terrifying because we're nobody, you know, I mean, the people

01:10:29.180 --> 01:10:34.280
making men in black were a very successful director, Barry Sonnenfeld, and a successful

01:10:34.280 --> 01:10:39.500
producer, Steven Spielberg, a successful company, Amblin with, you know, I mean, it was just

01:10:39.500 --> 01:10:41.020
