They thought he died in prison or whatever.

03:02:10.900 --> 03:02:14.220
It's like a whole like large group of people out there.

03:02:14.280 --> 03:02:18.920
And then you get into like, what constitutes evidence for what actually happened?

03:02:19.000 --> 03:02:21.140
And in certain cases you have physical evidence.

03:02:21.340 --> 03:02:23.840
In other cases you don't have any physical evidence.

03:02:23.840 --> 03:02:28.040
So then you get into these sort of tree falls in the woods, what, you know, but nobody's there

03:02:28.040 --> 03:02:28.540
to hear it.

03:02:28.540 --> 03:02:29.480
Like, what does that mean?

03:02:29.820 --> 03:02:34.800
And there's this neuroscientist, Wilder Penfield, who says that, you know, your, you know, false

03:02:34.800 --> 03:02:40.000
memories are indistinguishable from, you know, uh, real ones and you can implant false memories.

03:02:40.220 --> 03:02:46.740
So you get in a really trippy kind of Descartes demon territory where like maybe reality, maybe

03:02:46.740 --> 03:02:51.000
there are probable futures and probable pasts and a constricted present.

03:02:51.000 --> 03:02:56.500
And you have this zero one flipping and it flips to one in the present, but the past is

03:02:56.500 --> 03:02:59.760
like a much wider probability range and the future does too.

03:02:59.880 --> 03:03:04.260
And a lot of the quantum mechanics kind of godfathers flirted with ideas like this.

03:03:04.560 --> 03:03:09.200
And so, yeah, I mean, I think that's a model of reality that will become consensus.

03:03:09.560 --> 03:03:09.580
Yeah.

03:03:09.700 --> 03:03:12.460
So really quickly, cause it just, it jumps on what you just said.

